ress Forms to Help Your Cause</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10053:\"<p>Are wondering how to use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your cause? Besides simply asking people for money, there are other ways to take advantage of WPForms’ nonprofit form templates.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll outline the different ways you can use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your organization thrive.</p>\n<h3>1. Online Donations</h3>\n<p>Though creating an online donation form is the most obvious use for a nonprofit donation form, it would be wrong to not include it in our roundup. After all, if you’re trying to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/online-fundraising-ideas-for-nonprofits/\">raise money for your nonprofit organization</a>, like Mozilla , creating a simple online donation form is the quickest and easiest way.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273283\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page.png\" alt=\"mozilla donation page\" width=\"562\" height=\"344\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/mozilla-donation-page-300x184.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Plus, WPForms has some neat features that help <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/6-tactics-to-boost-donation-form-conversions/\">boost your donation form conversions</a> and generate you more money.</p>\n<p>Collecting money from donors is what’s going to keep your nonprofit alive. Luckily, WPForms makes collecting donations from people, using <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal</a> or <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe</a>, very simple.</p>\n<p>Even more exciting, our Stripe addon now has recurring payment capability so people that want to donate to your cause on a regular basis can just by filling out your donation form with their payment information.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261830\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png\" alt=\"enable recurring payments\" width=\"562\" height=\"390\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments-300x208.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>For help with setting up Stripe recurring, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-stripe-addon-with-wpforms/\">how to install and use the Stripe addon</a>.</p>\n<p>Here you’ll learn how to connect Stripe to your online donation form, add Stripe to your forms, enable recurring payments, and even set up smart conditional logic to make your donation forms more dynamic.</p>\n<h3>2. Volunteer Sign-Ups</h3>\n<p>When you stop and think about it, volunteers are what help your nonprofit organization carry out its mission.</p>\n<p>For instance, your organization may put on events like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Charity Auctions</li>\n<li>Sports Tournaments</li>\n<li>Walk/Run Race Events</li>\n<li>School-Wide Yard Sales</li>\n<li>Alumni Networking Dinners</li>\n<li>Holiday Gift Wrapping Services</li>\n<li>Community Bake Sales</li>\n<li>And so much more</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The thing is, in order for these types of events to run smoothly and generate the most money possible, either through event participation or donor sponsors, you’ll need a reliable crew of volunteers to help.</p>\n<p>Volunteers are vital for the before, during, and after of any nonprofit event. That’s why <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-set-up-a-volunteer-application-form-in-wordpress/\">creating a volunteer application form</a> on your website to get people to say they’ll help is so useful.</p>\n<p>For an example, take a look at the Sundance Festival’s volunteer application form:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273287\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example.png\" alt=\"volunteer form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"688\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/volunteer-form-example-245x300.png 245w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Your website reaches far and wide. Events that you’re hosting will spread throughout the community and those that want to get involved will be able to sign up easily on your site using your volunteer form.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-send-wpforms-entries-to-google-calendar\">WPForms integrates easily with Google Calendar</a> using our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">Zapier addon</a> so anytime someone agrees to volunteer for an event you’re hosting, the form entry will be sent directly to your team’s calendar. This way you never forget to staff an event properly.</p>\n<p>For those that can’t volunteer, but want to support your cause, just add a payment option to your volunteer form so they can donate.</p>\n<h3>3. Program Registrations</h3>\n<p>If your nonprofit offers help to those in need, like Love Your Brain does, consider adding a registration form to your website so people can sign up for the services you have available.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273284\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example.png\" alt=\"nonprofit registration example\" width=\"562\" height=\"606\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/nonprofit-registration-example-278x300.png 278w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>With a nonprofit registration form, you can gather important applicant information, vet applicants and choose those you want to accept, and easily manage all form entries in your WordPress dashboard to keep your programs and services running without a hitch.</p>\n<p>In addition, using any of the WPForms registration form templates, you can:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-clutter-free-forms-with-smart-logic/\">Use conditional logic</a> to take site visitors down the right registration path</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-multi-part-form-in-wordpress/\">Create multi-part forms</a> to fight form fatigue while collecting all required information</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">Create multiple form notifications</a> so you and your team receive the right information after forms are submitted</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-mailchimp-signup-checkbox-to-your-contact-form/\">Add a subscribe checkbox</a> to encourage people to sign up for future communication</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">Create multiple form confirmations</a> based on site visitor behavior</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Registration forms are not just for those who having paying customers that want to sign up for a program. Nonprofit organizations can offer their programs, free of charge, to those in need using the same type of form on their website.</p>\n<h3>4. Sponsorship Forms</h3>\n<p>Many nonprofits, such as the American Heart Association, rely on their big donors to sponsor events so they can continue to host them for the local community and those supporting their cause.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-273285\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example.png\" alt=\"sponsorship form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"579\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/sponsorship-form-example-291x300.png 291w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms has a Sponsorship Request Form template that makes it easy for corporations to get in touch and let you know they want to help fund your cause.</p>\n<p>So, give people a way to promote their business, get involved with a good cause, and boost your annual fundraising total.</p>\n<p>In addition, you can let companies <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-file-upload-form-in-wordpress/\">upload an image file of their business logo</a>, pay their sponsorship fee right away, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-service-agreements-in-wordpress-with-digital-signatures/\">sign with an electronic signature</a> to ensure the validity of the donation using the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/signature-addon/\">Signature addon</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-273288\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/electronic-signature-example.gif\" alt=\"electronic signature example\" width=\"562\" height=\"208\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to use nonprofit WordPress forms to help your cause.</p>\n<p>If you need some additional ideas, check out this roundup of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/online-fundraising-ideas-for-nonprofits/\">online fundraising ideas for nonprofit organizations</a>. And don’t forget to read up on <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to improve your email marketing efforts</a> so you can continue to build a bigger email list and reach a broader audience that wants to see your nonprofit succeed.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/unique-ways-to-use-nonprofit-wordpress-forms-to-help-your-cause/\">4 Unique Ways to Use Nonprofit WordPress Forms to Help Your Cause</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:89:\"https://wpforms.com/unique-ways-to-use-nonprofit-wordpress-forms-to-help-your-cause/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 17 Sep 2018 12:00:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"front end submissions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"calendar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=20715\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:585:\"<p>Do you want users to submit events to a calendar on your website? It can be a great time saver when you let your community help organize the events. In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress. Why Use an Event Submission Calendar? It&#8217;s helpful to have [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15096:\"<p>Do you want users to submit events to a calendar on your website? It can be a great time saver when you let your community help organize the events.</p>\n<p>In this article, we&#8217;ll show you how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Why Use an Event Submission Calendar?</h3>\n<p>It&#8217;s helpful to have an events calendar on your website for displaying&#8230;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>local community events</li>\n<li>organization functions</li>\n<li>sales or specials</li>\n<li>sports matches</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&#8230;and many other types of events for site visitors to see and attend.</p>\n<p>Allowing your users to submit events instead of adding them all yourself is a great way to engage your audience and save yourself some time. You can even <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/make-money-online\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">make money online</a> if you charge for event listings posted to your website&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a look at an easy way to allow users to add their events to your site&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create an Event Submission Form</h3>\n<p>The first thing you&#8217;ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">WPForms</a> plugin. Here’s a step by step guide on <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a WordPress plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/post-submissions-addon/\">Post Submissions addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Post Submissions</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-235134\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon.png\" alt=\"WPForms Post Submissions Addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Post-Submissions-Addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you’ll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>Check out out tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple contact form</a> as an example to get started.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s what our form looks like:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272020\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form.png\" alt=\"event calendar form\" width=\"562\" height=\"483\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-form-300x258.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In our form, we added these fields to the simple contact form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Event Title</strong> is a Single Line Text field</li>\n<li><strong>Start &amp; End Time</strong> are two Date/Time fields</li>\n<li><strong>Promotional Image</strong> is a File Upload field</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can add additional fields by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your user registration form.</p>\n<p>If you don&#8217;t want to customize a simple contact form, you might look into using the Event Planner Form template found in the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/form-templates/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>. This template comes with many of the form fields your site visitors will need to fill out to submit their event to your calendar.</p>\n<p>If you decide you want to monetize your website, and charge users to submit their event on your calendar, read this documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-users-to-choose-a-payment-method-on-your-form/\">how to allow users to choose a payment method</a> on your WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create a Calendar</h3>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll need to create a calendar for users to add their events to. For this, you can use <a title=\"The Events Calendar plugin in WordPress Repository\" href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/the-events-calendar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">The Events Calendar</a>. This is a free plugin for WordPress websites.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Plugins</strong> » <strong>Add New </strong>in your WordPress dashboard and search for &#8220;The Events Calendar&#8221; plugin.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Now </strong>and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272014\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin.png\" alt=\"the events calendar plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"419\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-plugin-300x224.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The Events Calendar is now ready for you to use.</p>\n<p>This plugin will create a <a title=\"how to create custom post types in WordPress\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/how-to-create-custom-post-types-in-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">custom post type</a> called <strong>Events </strong>that will appear in your WordPress dashboard. Custom post types work the same way that posts and pages work. The Events custom post type will, however, remain separate from your site&#8217;s posts and pages.</p>\n<p>You can preview the calendar that is created after installing and activating the plugin at <code>http://yoursite.com/events</code>.</p>\n<p>For now, it won&#8217;t show much information since you don&#8217;t have any events submitted yet.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Connect Your Form to Your Calendar</h3>\n<p>After setting up The Events Calendar plugin, you need to connect the form you&#8217;ve created to your calendar.</p>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings » Post Submissions </strong>in the form editor and turn post submissions <strong>On.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272015\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on.png\" alt=\"turn post submissions on\" width=\"562\" height=\"260\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/turn-post-submissions-on-300x139.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll want to match each field to the relevant part of the event custom post type.</p>\n<p>In our example we chose:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Event Title for the <strong>Post Title </strong>dropdown</li>\n<li>Description for the <strong>Post Content </strong>dropdown</li>\n<li>Promotional Image for the <strong>Post Featured Image </strong>dropdown</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We also set <strong>Post Type</strong> to Events (the custom post type created by enabling The Events Calendar plugin), and <strong>Post Status</strong> to Pending Review so that you can approve each submission before it goes live on your site.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272012\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings.png\" alt=\"post submissions settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"398\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/post-submissions-settings-300x212.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you can scroll down to the <strong>Custom Post Meta</strong> section.</p>\n<p>The last part of connecting your form to the calendar is to add just a bit of code here. This will connect the start and end times in your form to the start and end times in the calendar.</p>\n<p>We&#8217;ve shown you the code you need to include in the image below, but you can look up any other <a title=\"Events Calendar PRO WordPress post meta data\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/wordpress-post-meta-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">custom meta code</a> that The Events Calendar offers if you want to customize your calendar even more.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272019\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta.png\" alt=\"the events calendar custom meta\" width=\"562\" height=\"218\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/the-events-calendar-custom-meta-300x116.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Customize the Thank You Message</h3>\n<p>Before you publish your event submission form, it&#8217;s a good idea to change the default thank you message users will see.</p>\n<p>You can do this by going to <strong>Settings » Confirmation</strong>. In the preview panel, customize your message in any way you like.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272018\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message.png\" alt=\"customize confirmation message\" width=\"562\" height=\"310\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/customize-confirmation-message-300x165.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can also send users to a designated thank you page or a separate website altogether after they&#8217;ve submitted an event to your website&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>For help with these type of form confirmations, check out this helpful documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to set up form confirmations in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>For inspiration, you can also check out these helpful articles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">Effective Thank You page examples</a> that will boost user loyalty</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">Great success messages</a> you can display for site visitors</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For help with customizing multiple confirmation messages, check out <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-confirmations-in-wpforms/\">how to create multiple form confirmations in WPForms</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Publish Your User Submitted Events Form</h3>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your contact form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272017\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form.png\" alt=\"add user submitted events form\" width=\"562\" height=\"332\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/add-user-submitted-events-form-300x177.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your form will appear on your website and users can begin submitting their events.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Review and Publish Event Submissions</h3>\n<p>After your form is live on your site, you just need to approve the events users submit. To do this, go to <strong>Events</strong> in the WordPress dashboard.</p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll see that any submitted events will be listed as <strong>Pending</strong>. This means they need to be approved by you before they appear on your site&#8217;s calendar.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Edit</strong> underneath the event title.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272013\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission.png\" alt=\"review event submission\" width=\"562\" height=\"366\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/review-event-submission-300x195.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Preview the submission, taking special note of the <strong>Time &amp; Date</strong> near the bottom of your screen. This will be the time listed on your calendar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272024\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time.png\" alt=\"event calendar time\" width=\"562\" height=\"241\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/event-calendar-time-300x129.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re finished reviewing all the event details, click <strong>Publish</strong>. Then you can view your events calendar at <code>http://yoursite.com/events</code>.</p>\n<p>When the user hovers their mouse over the calendar event, they&#8217;ll see a preview popup. By clicking on it, they&#8217;ll get the full event listing.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-272025\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission.png\" alt=\"example calendar submission\" width=\"562\" height=\"343\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/example-calendar-submission-300x183.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a user submitted events calendar in WordPress using WPForms.</p>\n<p>Do you want to allow clients to schedule appointments on your work calendar? You might also want to check out our guide on <a title=\"How to Create a Client Booking Form in WordPress\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-client-booking-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a client booking form</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-user-submitted-events-calendar-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a User Submitted Events Calendar in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0: