:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7072:\"<p>Last week, we teased that we were on the verge of releasing one of the most requested features for WPForms.</p>\n<p>Well, the time has come.</p>\n<p>Today, we are extremely excited to announce that you can now accept recurring Stripe payments on any of your WordPress forms.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe Addon for WPForms</a> is one of our most popular addons. And for good reason.</p>\n<p>As the best online payment solution in the market, Stripe makes it easy to accept credit card payments online.</p>\n<p>Pair that with the fact that WPForms is the <strong>easiest and most beginner friendly WordPress form plugin</strong>, and you&#8217;re just asking for success.</p>\n<p>So, let’s take a look at what Stripe recurring functionality offers you and your customers!</p>\n<h3>WPForms Form Entry Improvements</h3>\n<p>One thing we boast about here at WPForms is how easy it is to manage all different kinds of form entries, even those that involve payments collected from customers.</p>\n<p>With Stripe recurring functionality now in full swing, we want to make sure you can quickly glance at your form entries and know immediately which payments are recurring, and which were one-time payments.</p>\n<p>So, we’ve introduced the recurring payment icon that appears next to any form entry that is now collecting regular payments.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261832\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/stripe-recurring-icon.png\" alt=\"stripe recurring icon\" width=\"562\" height=\"253\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/stripe-recurring-icon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/stripe-recurring-icon-300x135.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>But that’s not all.</p>\n<p>Now that you can offer recurring payments on your WordPress forms, we’ve updated how recurring payment entries look in the WordPress dashboard, so you can continue to manage payments with ease.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can see the value of each payment and the recurring schedule that was chosen by your customer.</p>\n<p>You also have the option to jump directly to your Stripe account to view the following by clicking on the available links:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Transaction ID:</strong> information about the actual payment that was processed</li>\n<li><strong>Subscription ID:</strong> details regarding the recurring payment</li>\n<li><strong>Customer ID:</strong> information about the customer who made a recurring payment</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261835\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/wpforms-entry-with-links.png\" alt=\"wpforms entry with links\" width=\"562\" height=\"307\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/wpforms-entry-with-links.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/wpforms-entry-with-links-300x164.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>We make switching between the WordPress dashboard and your Stripe account as seamless as possible so that managing customer payments doesn&#8217;t become a hassle.</p>\n<h3>Form Entry Data</h3>\n<p>In the past, when someone submitted a payment using your form, WPForms would send the Entry ID to your Stripe account for viewing.</p>\n<p>But that information alone isn’t really all that useful. So, we&#8217;ve made some changes.</p>\n<p>Now users can access their Stripe account and see which form the recurring payment came from, the Form ID, and the Entry ID.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261837\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/subscription-id.png\" alt=\"subscription id\" width=\"562\" height=\"364\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/subscription-id.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/subscription-id-300x194.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And to makes things even better, we’ve included a link to your Entry ID so you can easily jump from your Stripe account to your WordPress dashboard to view form entry information.</p>\n<p>Connecting WPForms with your Stripe account in the simplest way possible is our number one priority.</p>\n<p>But we also wanted to give you the opportunity to learn more about which forms are converting, so you can grow your business and generate more revenue.</p>\n<h3>WPForms Payment Settings</h3>\n<p>Last, but not least, we want to give you a sneak peak into how the payment settings in the form builder have changed to accommodate this exciting new functionality.</p>\n<p>Before, when configuring your Stripe payment settings, all you had to do was enable Stripe payments, determine a receipt setting, and enable conditional logic if you wanted to.</p>\n<p>Now, once you enable recurring payments, you’ll see additional settings to configure recurring payments to match your needs.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261830\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png\" alt=\"enable recurring payments\" width=\"562\" height=\"390\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/enable-recurring-payments-300x208.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To start, name your plan and choose a recurring time period:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Daily</li>\n<li>Weekly</li>\n<li>Monthly</li>\n<li>Quarterly</li>\n<li>Semi-yearly</li>\n<li>Yearly</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Next, select Customer Email so Stripe can create a customer profile.</p>\n<p>And now for the best part &#8211; <strong>enable conditional logic</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-261831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/recurring-conditional-logic.png\" alt=\"recurring conditional logic\" width=\"562\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/recurring-conditional-logic.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/recurring-conditional-logic-300x107.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to let customers choose between making a one-time payment or setting up recurring payments, then you need to enable conditional logic. This will trigger recurring payment functionality when your customer selects that option on your payment form.</p>\n<p>And there you have it!</p>\n<p>I know it took us a while, but we&#8217;re glad to get this feature released.</p>\n<p>As always, thank you for your continued support of WPForms, and we look forward to helping you create better online forms!</p>\n<p><em>Lindsay and the WPForms team</em></p>\n<p>P.S. Don’t have a WPForms Pro license? <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">Click here to get started today</a> and experience the WPForms difference.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/new-stripe-recurring-functionality-for-your-payment-forms/\">[NEW] Stripe Recurring Functionality for WPForms is Finally Here!</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:83:\"https://wpforms.com/new-stripe-recurring-functionality-for-your-payment-forms/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"6\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"Single vs. Multi-Part WordPress Forms: Learn What’s Best and Why\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"https://wpforms.com/single-vs-multi-part-wordpress-forms-learn-whats-best-and-why/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://wpforms.com/single-vs-multi-part-wordpress-forms-learn-whats-best-and-why/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 05 Sep 2018 12:00:04 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"form conversion rate\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"multi-part form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"form abandonment\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"form fields\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=264395\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:617:\"<p>Have you ever wondered whether it’s better to use a single or multi-part form on your WordPress website? Knowing when it’s best to use each and why will help you boost form conversions and give site visitors the best user experience possible. In this article, we’ll take a look at single vs. multi-part WordPress forms [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/single-vs-multi-part-wordpress-forms-learn-whats-best-and-why/\">Single vs. Multi-Part WordPress Forms: Learn What&#8217;s Best and Why</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10939:\"<p>Have you ever wondered whether it’s better to use a single or multi-part form on your WordPress website? Knowing when it’s best to use each and why will help you boost form conversions and give site visitors the best user experience possible.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll take a look at single vs. multi-part WordPress forms and help you discover when you should use either one on your site to get people to take action and submit their forms.</p>\n<h3>Single-Step WordPress Forms</h3>\n<p>You know the saying, “less is more.” And we happen to agree that most of the time, when it comes to creating forms on your website, simple, single-step forms are the best.</p>\n<p>After all, <a href=\"https://www.quicksprout.com/2013/01/31/how-to-optimize-contact-forms-for-conversions/?display=wide\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Quicksprout claims</a> that by limiting the number of form fields on your website to just three, you can get a minimum conversion rate of 25%.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-2355\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/quicksproutcasestudy.jpg\" alt=\"QuickSprout Infographic explaining the number of fields\" width=\"562\" height=\"221\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/quicksproutcasestudy.jpg 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/quicksproutcasestudy-300x118.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Adding to that, <a href=\"http://blog.hubspot.com/blog/tabid/6307/bid/6746/Which-Types-of-Form-Fields-Lower-Landing-Page-Conversions.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">a study by Hubspot</a> shows that by reducing the number of form fields from four to three, you can improve conversion rates by as much as 50%.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-264436\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conversion-rate-and-form-fields.png\" alt=\"conversion rate and form fields\" width=\"562\" height=\"430\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conversion-rate-and-form-fields.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/conversion-rate-and-form-fields-300x230.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>These are not statistics you can afford to ignore, and can make a big difference in how successful you become.</p>\n<p>Single-step forms are the most common type of form on people’s websites. They are easy to create, especially when using <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>, and include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">Simple contact forms</a> so people can get in touch with you or your team</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-campaign-monitor-subscribe-form-in-wordpress/\">Subscribe forms</a> to boost your <a href=\"http://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">email marketing efforts</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-nonprofit-donation-form/\">Donation forms</a> for supporting your cause</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">User registration forms</a> so people can access locked content</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-net-promoter-score-nps-survey-in-wordpress/\">Net Promoter Score surveys</a> for gauging customer loyalty</li>\n<li>And so much more</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218829\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Final Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"334\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>These types of forms ask for very little information, are quick and easy to fill out, and have no need for multiple steps that carry over into other form pages.</p>\n<h3>When to Use Single-Step WordPress Forms</h3>\n<p>Aside from the evidence that shorter forms usually convert the highest, there are some reasons why you might opt for a single-step form on your website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If you only need a small amount of information from users</li>\n<li>When people are just becoming aware of your brand and what you have to offer</li>\n<li>When enticing site visitors to perform a specific call to action</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you can keep your forms distraction-free, people are more likely to finish filling them out and submit them.</p>\n<p>That said, if you try to cram too many form fields onto a single-step form, and refuse to carry some of the fields over to another form page, you may overwhelm site visitors and cause them to abandon their form before submitting it.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why sometimes using a multi-part form is best.</p>\n<h3>Multi-Part WordPress Forms</h3>\n<p>If we always say that the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/ways-to-fix-your-low-converting-contact-forms/\">best way to design your WordPress forms</a> is to keep your forms short, you may be wondering why we offer the ability to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-multi-part-form-in-wordpress/\">create multi-part forms in WPForms</a>.</p>\n<p>Multi-part forms include many pages of form fields that people must fill out before being able to click submit.</p>\n<p>And while they can become lengthy, one study found that <a href=\"https://www.business2community.com/online-marketing/testing-2-step-vs-1-step-conversion-forms-022833#uxQzVTMVADIoBZgz.97\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">14% more people</a> finished filling out a multi-part form on their site than the single-step form. And to top it off, this even included those that paused filling out the form, and later came back to finish.</p>\n<p>But why would that happen? After all, shorter forms are less daunting, easier to fill out, and have seemingly proven to have higher conversion rates.</p>\n<h3>Why Use a Multi-Part WordPress Form</h3>\n<p>Though determining the exact reason why some people prefer to fill out multi-step forms is largely subjective, it has been suggested that those that are more invested in the process of filling out a longer form and those that have more to gain from finishing don’t mind.</p>\n<p>Not to mention, sometimes you just need to gather a lot of information from people submitting forms on your website.</p>\n<p>And, rather than make one long, never-ending, single-step form that people have to scroll through to finish, it’s a better option to break that form into multiple parts to fight form fatigue and increase conversions.</p>\n<p>Multi-part forms are perfect when you need to create a:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-client-booking-form-in-wordpress/\">Client booking form</a> that collects booking information on one page and payment information on another</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job application form</a> that requires a lot of user information be collected</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-request-a-quote-form-in-wordpress/\">Request a quote form</a>, especially if you offer a lot of services that people may want</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-t-shirt-order-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">Complex order form</a> that collects payment from customers right away</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-set-up-a-volunteer-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Volunteer application form</a> when you’re hosting an event you need help with</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Multi-part forms require a lot of information from site visitors. Luckily, WPForms comes with customizable progress bars to guide site visitors through your lengthy form so they know exactly where they’re at in the process at all times.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-230947\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Progress-Bar.png\" alt=\"WPForms Progress Bar\" width=\"562\" height=\"288\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Progress-Bar.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WPForms-Progress-Bar-300x154.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In addition, you can <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-clutter-free-forms-with-smart-logic/\">enable smart logic</a> so users only see the form fields that relate to them based on their behavior as they fill out your forms. By hiding form fields that people don’t need to fill out, you’ll speed up the process and boost form submissions.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-19255\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/conditional-logic-1.gif\" alt=\"conditional smart logic service example\" width=\"620\" height=\"350\" /></p>\n<p>If you need some inspiration, be sure to check out our roundup of <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/excellent-multi-page-form-examples-for-your-inspiration/\">multi-page examples in the real world that do well</a>.</p>\n<p>Lastly, if you want to unlock more leads, even when people find your lengthy forms too much to finish filling out before they leave, take advantage of WPForms’ <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-abandonment-addon/\">Form Abandonment addon</a>.</p>\n<p>With it, you can save partial form entries and follow up with those that initially showed interest in what you have to offer. You can even automate the process and send out an email to anyone that <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-combat-order-form-abandonment-and-increase-your-sales/\">abandons your form before submitting it</a>.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! The simplest explanation there is when it comes to single vs. multi-part WordPress forms. Of course, every situation is different, and your site visitors may react very differently to single-step or multi-step forms than another target audience might.</p>\n<p>That’s why it’s important you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/5-best-ab-testing-plugins-and-tools-for-your-wordpress-forms/\">always A/B test your website’s forms</a> to see what&#8217;s working and how you can make improvements to increase your form’s conversion rates. That&#8217;s the only true way to know which type of form, single or multi-part, is best for you.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/single-vs-multi-part-wordpress-forms-learn-whats-best-and-why/\">Single vs. Multi-Part WordPress Forms: Learn What&#8217;s Best and Why</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:87:\"https://wpforms.com/single-vs-multi-part-wordpress-forms-learn-whats-best-and-why/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:25:\"https://wpforms.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"heade